  "prompt": "What is Google's internal code review policy/process?",
  "response": "Google's internal code review process is designed to ensure high code quality, promote collaboration among engineers, and facilitate knowledge sharing. While the exact details of the code review process may vary across teams and projects, some general principles and practices are commonly followed at Google, including:\n\n1. **Peer Review**: Code changes are typically reviewed by peers before being merged into the main codebase. This helps catch bugs, improve code quality, and foster best practices.\n\n2. **Automated Testing**: Before a code change is reviewed, it usually undergoes automated testing to catch basic errors. Tests may include unit tests, integration tests, and end-to-end tests to ensure the new code interacts well with existing systems.\n\n3. **Code Review Tools**: Google employs internal tools (like Critique or a version of Gerrit) for managing code reviews. These tools allow developers to submit their code changes, comment, and track feedback efficiently.\n\n4. **Guidelines and Checklists**: There are established guidelines and checklists for reviewers to reference, which may cover coding standards, documentation requirements, and architectural considerations.\n\n5. **Descriptive Pull Requests**: Developers are encouraged to write clear and detailed descriptions of the changes they\u2019re proposing, including rationale, potential impacts, and any relevant issue links. This helps reviewers understand the context and purpose of the changes.\n\n6. **Responsive Feedback**: Reviewers are expected to provide constructive and respectful feedback. Developers are encouraged to engage in discussions, clarify doubts, and iterate on their changes based on the feedback received.\n\n7. **Timeframe for Reviews**: Google typically encourages timely reviews to maintain workflow efficiency\u2014reviewers are expected to respond within a reasonable timeframe to keep projects moving forward.\n\n8. **Ownership and Accountability**: Engineers are generally expected to take ownership of their code and actively participate in the code review process, both as authors and reviewers.\n\n9. **Continuous Learning**: The process also supports a culture of continuous learning where developers are encouraged to learn from reviews, both through giving and receiving feedback.\n\n10. **Diversity of Perspectives**: Google promotes having a diverse set of reviewers to ensure different perspectives in the review process, enhancing code quality and promoting inclusivity in discussions.\n\nOverall, Google\u2019s code review process is integral to its engineering culture, aimed at maintaining high standards of quality and fostering a collaborative environment among teams.",
